  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contracts in Oregon totaled $1.2B in FY2026 to date. Obligations fell 40.7% year over year while buyers issued 6,725 awards with an average award size of $184K. The Department of Defense accounted for $622M of the current-year obligations, followed by the Department of Agriculture with $154M and the Department of Transportation with $129M. Top vendors receiving obligations in FY2026 to date include VIGOR MARINE LLC with $310M, COLLINS ELBIT VISION SYSTEMS, LLC with $70.9M, and GE RENEWABLES US LLC with $66.7M. By industry, Ship Building and Repairing led with $323M and Other Heavy and Civil Engineering Construction followed with $145M. Historical annual obligations show higher full-year totals in prior years, including $2.5B in FY23 and $2.4B in FY24, with FY26 at $1.2B to date. All figures are contract obligations; current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date).",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How have Oregon federal contract obligations changed recently?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 40.7% year over year and stand at $1.2B for FY2026 to date. Full fiscal-year comparisons show prior totals of $2.5B in FY23 and $2.4B in FY24, with FY26 currently at $1.2B. The number of awards issued in FY2026 to date is 6,725 with an average award size of $184K."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Which agencies and industries dominate Oregon federal spending?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense is the largest buyer with $622M in obligations for FY2026 to date, followed by the Department of Agriculture with $154M and the Department of Transportation with $129M. By industry, Ship Building and Repairing leads with $323M and Other Heavy and Civil Engineering Construction with $145M. Major vendors include VIGOR MARINE LLC with $310M and COLLINS ELBIT VISION SYSTEMS, LLC with $70.9M."
      }
    ]
  },
